cal texts as well as modern texts by Heidegger, Arendt, Camus, and others. Central to his project is a rigorous distinction between conventional, finite hospitality, with its many conditions, and the aspirational idea of hospitality as something offered unconditionally to the stranger. This volume collects the first year of the seminar.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aOther (Philosophy) 0aOther (Philosophy). 0aOther minds (Theory of knowledge) 0aOther minds (Theory of knowledge). 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aBrault, Pascale-Anne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurt, E. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKamuf, Peggy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226828022423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226828022/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles